White will push for LB1 overall numbers this season if the Bucs continue to let him put his pass rush skills to use. He is locked in as a top-five option for Week 2 against New Orleans.

Parsons is locked in as a top-five option regardless of opponent but has an especially tasty matchup this week against a Bengals team that looked discombobulated during Week 1. He had four solos, one assist, two sacks, and two tackles for loss against the Bucs and will continue to see snaps at linebacker and on the edge.

KGH was a bit of a forgotten man once the Texans added hotshot SEC rookie Christian Harris in the 2022 NFL Draft. However, with Harris on IR and set to miss at least the first four games, KGH will get all of the snaps he can handle. He responded with 14 solos, four assists, and one pass defended against the Colts and will be an elite LB2 option for his Week 2 matchup against the Denver Broncos. Denver will run the ball enough to keep him busy, especially if the Texans fall behind, as expected. KGH should be started at least until his Week 6 bye.

Bolton put his LB1 upside on display in Week 1, tallying eight solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. He led all Chiefs linebackers with 77 percent of the snaps and remains an elite LB2 option for Week 2 against the Chargers.

Cody Barton was elite in Week 1, recording eight solos, two assists, one sack, and two tackles for loss. He should have more LB1 level weeks left in him and should be treated as a high upside LB2 option going forward.

Hicks thrived in his first game as a Minnesota Viking, racking up nine solos, five assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. He will look to keep the good times rolling against a Lions team that funneled 31 of 49 available touches to their running backs in Week 1. Hicks is in the LB2 conversation for Week 2, and for as long as he can keep up the hot play.
Edwards played every snap in Week 1 and appears locked in the middle regardless of Nakobe Dean's development or lack thereof. He will be a strong LB3 with LB2 upside for Week 2.

Long was solid in Week 1 and is an LB2 option for Monday Night Football against the Buffalo Bills. His five solo, three assist line from Week 1 is not going to wow anyone, but is steady enough, and we know there is upside for more.

LVE looked to be back to his Pro Bowl form during Week 1's contest, a sign that he may finally be nearing full health after incessant injuries plagued a once-promising career. He managed six solos and three assists in Week 1, putting him squarely in the mix as an LB2 option.

Quincy was solid to open the season, recording six solos and one sack. He profiles as a DB2 option after a breakout campaign in 2021. Start him wherever possible for a plus Week 2 matchup against the Browns.

Werner has finally arrived. A long-time dynasty darling due to the aging situation in the middle in New Orleans, Werner had his breakout game in Week 1, racking up 12 solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and one forced fumble. He should be just as active in Week 2 against Tampa Bay and should be viewed as an LB2 option. He proved he has LB1 upside but will need to string together a few more strong weeks before he enters that discussion.

Mykal recorded four solos, two assists, one sack, two tackles for loss, and one forced fumble while playing an every snap role against the Saints. His snap count alone puts him in the LB3 conversation, and if he can keep producing, it will not be long before he enters the LB2 conversation. Start him until further notice.

Isaiah Simmons remains one of the most frustrating players in fantasy. Dripping with upside as a safety, the Cardinals instead stuck him at the less valuable off-ball linebacker spot for his first two seasons and now have him in the STAR role. The STAR role is one that Simmons is much more suited for as it more closely matches what he did in college and what he had success with last season. Simmons would be a weekly DB1 if he qualified there, but instead, we are forced to wait for Yahoo to update his role, something which may not happen since he wears the green dot and practices with the linebackers. As a linebacker, he is too inconsistent to trust as much more than a low-end LB2/high-end LB3 as opposed to a DB1, especially now that he will be spending more time in coverage. Keep Simmons benched if you are in need of an LB1 or if you have other LB2 options.

With Simmons playing the STAR role which calls for him to play a lot of coverage, Zaven is the linebacker to roster from Arizona. He played more snaps than Simmons in Week 1 and recorded a solid four solos and three assists. He is a DB2 option for Week 2 against Las Vegas. The Raiders surrendered the 12th most points to the position during Week 1.
Jamin managed just three solos despite playing 93 percent of the snaps against the Jaguars. He has the tools of a high-end LB2, but until he shows some consistency, he is more of an LB3/flex option.

Anzalone was excellent in Week 1, recording seven solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. He has the opportunity for another big day against a Commanders team that allowed the second most fantasy points to the position in Week 1. Start him as a LB3 with LB2 upside.

Brown should see more snaps this weekend with Denzel Perryman sidelined and is a strong LB3 option. Fantasy managers are understandably a little disappointed that he did not see an every snap role with Perryman out of the game, but he should still see 70 plus percent of the snaps and have ample opportunity for tackle production.

Mack went off against his original team in Week 1, racking up five solos, one assist, three sacks, four tackles for loss, and one forced fumble. He is likely rostered on providers where he has DE eligibility, but for those still on Yahoo, he is currently listed as an LB only. Mack had just six sacks last season but is poised to crack double digits again alongside Joey Bosa. Mack should post LB2 numbers this season and should be started on squads that can start two or more LBs every week.

Highsmith went off in Week 1, recording six solos, three assists, three sacks, three tackles for loss, and a forced fumble. He dominated snaps from the right side and will maintain a high usage role as long as he is cooking. He gets the New England Patriots in Week 2, a team that allowed the 12th most fantasy points to edge rushers in 2021. Highsmith will not get three sacks against the Pats but should rack up tackles against the run. Highsmith should be started wherever possible, even without T.J. Watt occupying multiple blockers.

Jones was rock solid in Week 1 despite the presence of Bobby Wagner and is a strong flex/LB3 option for Week 2. He can work his way into the LB2 conversation if he shows he can be consistent, but expectations should be tempered until he does.

Will Gay is dripping with upside but has yet to put it together on a consistent basis. As such, he has yet to secure a full-time role, limiting his tackle opportunities week-to-week. He is a solid deep league flex/LB4, but fantasy managers should look elsewhere if looking for an LB2 for Week 2.

Chubb put up excellent numbers against Seattle but was less disruptive than his four solo, one assist, two sack, two tackle for loss, and one forced fumble line may indicate. He could have a truly monster performance in store if he can put together more strong pass rush snaps.

Von was an absolute monster against Los Angeles in the season opener, finishing the night with four solos, two sacks, and three tackles for loss. He was in the backfield all night, and it figures to be much of the same against Tennessee on Monday night. The Titans will look to run the ball until they fall behind, at which point, look out. The Bills defense is plain nasty.

Nwosu was excellent to start the season, notching defensive player of the week honors on the strength of three solos, four assists, one sack, one tackle for loss, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. He played 89 percent of the snaps and should be locked into a near-everydown role when he is playing well. He has more value on providers where he has DE/DL eligibility but is still a solid LB3 option for Yahoo users.

The Hard Knocks star recorded four solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss in his debut and should continue to rack up production. He is nothing more than a deep league LB3 option for now, but he has a chance to enter the LB2 conversation if he can stay on the field and avoid mental lapses.

Van Noy played just 48 percent of the snaps in Week 1, making him more of a bench stash than someone you want to trot out there for Week 2. He has the tools to soak up snaps both inside and outside, so he remains a hold even if he remains behind Kenneth Murray and Drue Tranqull.

Dean saw just three defensive snaps during Week 1 and was probably only active due to his participation on special teams (15 snaps). He has LB2 upside when he finally starts to see regular snaps but is a bench stash only in the deepest of redraft leagues.

Murray surprisingly emerged as the snap leader at inside linebacker for the Chargers, a sign that he may have finally turned the corner in his development as far as the coaching staff is concerned. This immediately places him on the LB3 periphery, even if his three solo, two assist outing in Week 1 left more to be desired.

Derwin remains locked in as the DB1 overall for Week 2. He gets a plus matchup against Travis Kelce and the Kansas City Chiefs and should be ready to explode under the bright lights of Thursday Night Football.

Harrison Smith was back in his bag of old tricks in Week 1, racking up five solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. Smith has been a DB1 fixture and figures to stay there for a plus Week 2 matchup against what should be a run-heavy attack.

Minkah went off in Week 1, to the tune of 10 solos, four assists, one interception, one pass defended, one blocked kick, and one touchdown. He has never been the most consistent contributor in the tackle department but he's able to put together monster games like this that keep him in the DB1 discussion. Lock him in as just that for a plus matchup against what should be a ground and short pass-heavy attack from New England.

Budda had seven solos and six assists in the opener and will look for another double-digit tackle performance in Week 2 against the Las Vegas Raiders. Budda is locked in as a top-five DB1 option this weekend.

Walker was excellent in Week 1, racking up nine solos, two assists, two tackles for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. He will be in the DB1 conversation for most of the season and Week 1 served as a reminder of his top-five upside. He gets Washington in Week 2, a matchup that should keep him busy with constant work underneath.

Jalen Thompson had nine solos in the opener, reminding us all that he has DB1 upside when things are clicking. He looks poised for another strong outing this week against Las Vegas. Start him as a DB2 option.

Abram is locked into a near-every-down role with Trevor Moehrig sidelined and will look for a repeat of his Week 1 explosion this weekend against the Cardinals. Coming off a nine solo, three assist performance, Abram is in the DB1 conversation for Week 2.

Teammate Jevon Holland gets more of the IDP love, but Brandon Jones was the shiny new IDP rookie that managers were salivating about not too long ago. He reminded us of why he was so highly regarded by racking up six solos, five assists, one sack, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. He gets a plus matchup against Lamar Jackson and the Baltimore Ravens in Week 2, firmly entrenching him as a strong DB2 option.

L'Jarius was excellent in Week 1, once again teasing him saliva inducing IDP upside. He recorded eight solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. He will go on a short week against the Los Angeles Chargers and should see enough work to be a CB1/DB2 for Week 2. Keenan Allen's pending absence means he will get less work in the slot, but he should still stay busy all over the formation.

Hufanga was excellent in Week 1, racking up nine solos, two assists, three tackles for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. He played a near every snap role and looks to be coming into his own as a steady IDP contributor. Hufanga played more than half of his snaps in the box, which is something that should propel him into the upper echelon DB2 conversation immediately.

One solo and three assists is not going to cut it for a player fantasy managers are relying on as a DB2 option. Thankfully brighter days are ahead and could start as soon as this against Atlanta. Plug Rapp in as a DB2 option thanks to the plus matchup against Marcus Mariota and co.

Ramsey recorded six solos on Thursday Night Football and should continue to be one of the most productive IDP cornerbacks thanks to being featured in the STAR role for the Rams defense. Consider him a CB1/DB2 option for a plus Week 2 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Owens exploded in Week 1, tallying 11 solos, four assists, and one pass defended. This may very well go down as one of his, if not his best game of the season, but he flashed enough upside to be rostered in leagues where you can start two or more S or DB. He played enough snaps to be taken seriously, and if he can produce another strong game will place himself squarely on the DB2 border. He is someone those in deeper leagues will want to check the wire for immediately.
Epps went off in Week 1, racking up eight solos, two assists, and one tackle for loss. Epps played every snap and is a DB3 with DB2 upside going forward.

Forrest was excellent in relief on the inactive Kam Curl, tallying four solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, one interception, two passes defended, and one forced fumble. His fantasy value currently ties to the health of Curl, but he should have earned himself an increased role with this performance. He is someone to add to the watch list or add if you also have Curl on your roster.

Williams was excellent against the Jets in Week 1, recording 10 solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. The former second round pick started off his tenure as a Raven with a bang and will look to keep the momentum going against the Miami Dolphins in Week 2. Williams has never been an elite option for IDP purposes but could become a reliable upside DB2 option in the Ravens defensive scheme. He is worth a roster spot in leagues of all sizes.

Deablo dominated middle linebacker snaps once Denzel Perryman left Week 1's contest with an ankle injury, playing ahead of veteran Jayon Brown. Perryman missed practice all week and has been ruled out for  Week 2. Perryman being inactive bodes well for Deablo's Week 2 fantasy value against the Arizona Cardinals. Arizona gifted the ninth most fantasy points to the position in Week 1 and should provide plenty of tackle opportunities for the linebackers this week. Arizona is likely to be ground-heavy when possible, which should help Deablo push for DB1/LB2 numbers once again. Start Deablo wherever possible.

CJGJ was solid in the opener, tallying five solos and a pass defended, and remains a DB2 option for Week 2 against Minnesota. He should push for DB1 numbers once he is more comfortable in the Eagles scheme.

Hamilton managed just three solos in his NFL debut, but the future remains bright. He is still a DB2 option, albeit a risky one, against the Dolphins. For those in deeper leagues, deploying him as a DB3 with elite DB2 upside makes more sense.

Josh Jones came on in relief of the injured Jamal Adams and is expected to assume starter snaps until further notice. Jones managed four solos and three assists against Seattle and should be an upside DB3 for as long as maintains regular snaps.

Fuller is an ocean-deep league bench stash at best as long as he is playing a backup role for the Rams. He has proven he can be a low-end DB2 option when starting, so those in deeper leagues with the bench size to do so should hold.

Nate Hobbs racked up the fantasy points in Week 1, totaling six solos, three assists, two tackles for loss, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. He will not produce like this on a weekly basis, but this glimpse of his upside puts him on the CB2/DB3 radar.

Okudah piled up the fantasy points in Week 1, tallying seven solos, three assists, one tackle for loss, and one pass defended. He will not produce like this on a weekly basis, but the tackle upside makes him an intriguing CB1 option in CB leagues.

Troy Hill was a busy man in Week 1, racking up six solos, two assists, one interception, and one pass defended. This very well may go down as his top fantasy output of the season, but he is still a viable CB2/DB4 option. He is worth a look for a plus Week 2 matchup against the Atlanta Falcons.

Cornerbacks are often among the most volatile IDP players, but there are a few who are elite tacklers who make a case for DB2 or even DB1 consideration, and Desmond King is one of them. King racked up five solos, one assist, one tackle for loss, and two passes defended in Week 1, and should be among the defensive back tackle leaders at the end of the season, not just cornerbacks. His 68 solos last season placed him 13th among all defensive backs and second among all cornerbacks. King should be plugged in all formats in which you must start two or more DB's.

In case you missed it and wondered who Nick Scott is, Scott won the starting safety job over the likes of Jordan Fuller and Terrell Burgess. He had a solid Week 1 line with three solos, four assists, one forced fumble, and one pass defended. Head coach Sean McVay loves the hard-hitting safety, which means Fuller needs to stay glued to fantasy benches while Scott needs to be rostered and started as a DB3 option. We have yet to see Scott's actual upside, but the fact that he won the job over Fuller and Burgess should be an endorement of what he brings to the table. For this week, Scott has DB2 upside against an Atlanta Falcons team that simply gifted fantasy points to the position during Week 1.

Witherspoon had a DB1 performance in Week 1, racking up six solos, two assists, one tackle for loss, one interception, and one pass defended. He should continue to see a lot of targets in coverage, making him an intriguing CB2/DB3 target.

Cine missed the opener with a knee injury but is expected to make his debut on Monday Night Football. Cine turned some heads in the offseason and is expected to be the top rookie IDP safety behind Kyle Hamilton. He is a DB3 option for Week 2.
Neal played zero defensive snaps last week and needs to be left on benches until he cements a role on defense.
Sorensen played zero defensive snaps in his Saints debut, instead playing a full-time special teams role. He is not a fantasy option until further notice.
